  "notes": "This is a natural experiment study exploiting government bans of ChatGPT to estimate causal effects on software development activity. The paper employs three quasi-experimental methods (DID, Synthetic Control, and Synthetic Difference-in-Differences) and reports results across multiple outcomes at both the aggregate country level and the country-programming language level. The study design consists of 120 treatment units (countries with ChatGPT access) and 27 control units (countries without access), with 11 pre-treatment periods and 2 treatment periods. The treatment period begins in Q4 2022 when ChatGPT was launched on November 30th. Results show generally positive effects of ChatGPT availability on code pushes, repositories, and developers across most programming languages, though the magnitude and statistical significance vary by method. One notable exception is TSQL, which shows a negative DID coefficient. The authors note potential concerns about code quality and suggest future research should examine long-term impacts on code quality, developer skills, and broader economic implications.",
  "_paper_id": "2406.11046v1"
}